  "opinion": "As a carpenter who’s spent decades building things with my hands, I’ve noticed how science often feels like a separate world—something that’s not always accessible to folks like me who didn’t go through the traditional academic path. The gender gap in science isn’t just about women being underrepresented; it’s about how the system itself can exclude people from all backgrounds. I’ve seen it in my own community: neighbors who’ve worked hard but never got the chance to study in the way that’s expected for science careers. My parents, one with a bachelor’s and the other a PhD, taught me that curiosity matters more than credentials, but the system often rewards formal education over practical skills. Should we address it? Absolutely. We need to create pathways that don’t require a degree to get into science. Think about how I’ve taught my kids to build things—they learn through doing, not just books. If we could have more hands-on science programs for kids who aren’t in traditional schools, that might help close the gap. It’s not about changing science itself, but making sure everyone has the chance to contribute. After all, science isn’t just for those who’ve been in labs all their lives—it’s for anyone who’s willing to ask questions and try things out.",
